    "summary": "Alexander the Great's campaigns in Central Asia (329–327 BC) were the most grueling and brutal phase of his conquests, as he pushed through Bactria (modern Afghanistan) and Sogdia (modern Uzbekistan/Tajikistan) in pursuit of Bessus, the Bactrian satrap who had murdered Darius III and claimed the Persian throne. Unlike the set-piece battles of his western campaigns, Central Asia required years of guerrilla warfare against mountain tribes and nomadic resistance led by leaders like Spitamenes.\n\nAlexander founded numerous garrison cities (many named Alexandria) across the region to anchor his control, and married the Bactrian noblewoman Roxana — a calculated political alliance that shocked his Macedonian officers. His behavior in this period showed increasing autocratic tendencies: he murdered his general Cleitus in a drunken rage, attempted to impose Persian-style proskynesis (prostration before the king), and executed his court historian Callisthenes for refusing this custom. Despite the prolonged resistance, Alexander incorporated Bactrian cavalry into his army and left a lasting Greek cultural presence in the region, later manifested in the [[event:1173|Greco-Bactrian Kingdom]].",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_the_Great#Bactria_and_Sogdia",
